egory:Samsunspor footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Augsburg players]]\n[[Category:Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf players]]\n[[Category:Stade d'Abidjan players]]\n[[Category:Santos FC Ouagadougou footballers]]\n[[Category:Helsingin Jalkapalloklubi players]]\n[[Category:FC Irtysh Pavlodar players]]\n[[Category:Chippa United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Riga FC players]]\n[[Category:ASEC Mimosas players]]\n[[Category:Al Masry SC players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcper Lig players]]\n[[Category:Veikkausliiga players]]\n[[Category:UAE Pro League players]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Finland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in South Africa]]\n[[Category:2012 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2013 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2015 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Ivorian emigrants to Burkina Faso]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Abidjan]]\n[[Category:2017 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:US des Forces Arm\u00e9es players]]\n[[Category:Horoya AC players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Guinea]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in Guinea]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in Finland]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 expatriate sportspeople in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in Guinea]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in Finland]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:Ivorian expatriate sportspeople in South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Omvrasan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristide_Banc%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "RaFia Santana", "text_new": "{{short description|Black American artist and musician}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = RaFia Santana <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| alt = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1990}}\n| birth_place = Brooklyn, NY\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality = American\n| education = SUNY Purchase College\n| alma_mater = [[SUNY Purchase College]]\n| known_for = [[Electronic Music]], [[New Media Art]], [[Performance art ]]\n| notable_works = 'Ain't Nothin', 'Dizzillusionz', 'Worked'\n| style = \n| movement = [[Conceptual art|Conceptual]], [[Internet Art]], [[New Media Art]], [[Postinternet]]\n| spouse = \n| awards = Rhizome MicroGrant, 2015<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2015 Net Art Microgrants |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2015/sep/09/announcing-2015-rhizome-internet-art-microgrants/ |website=Rhizome |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n| elected = \n| patrons = \n| memorials = \n| website = https://raf-i-a.tumblr.com/\n| module = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n\n'''RaFia Santana''' is an African American artist, musician, and performer based in Brooklyn, NY.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cepeda |first1=Gaby |title=Artist Profile: Rafia Santana |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2016/aug/10/artist-profile-rafia-santana/ |website=Rhizome}}</ref> Her work ranges from animated gifs<ref>{{cite web |title=NFSW GIF of the Hump Day: Rafia Santana |url=http://dallasartdealers.org/nfsw-gif-of-the-hump-day-rafia-santana/ |website=Dallas Art Dealers |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> to self-portraiture,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eler |first1=Alicia |title=In Search of the Authentic Selfie |url=https://hyperallergic.com/410585/in-search-of-the-authentic-selfie/ |website=HyperAllergic}}</ref> videos, and performance to editioned clothing and electronic music exploring gentrification, the millennial mindset, mental health, and the lived black experience.<ref>{{cite web |title=RaFia Santana |url=https://www.blackportraitures.info/?person=rafiasantana |website=Black Portraiture[s] |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dizzillusions |url=http://arts.timessquarenyc.org/times-square-arts/projects/midnight-moment/dizzillusions/index.aspx |website=Time Square Arts}}</ref> They use the internet as a medium to share their artwork, empower black and brown communities, and challenge ideas of solidarity and alliance. She had exhibitions and/or performances at the Eyebeam<ref>{{cite web |title=AFTERCARE WITH EYEBEAM + ICP |url=http://topicalcream.info/blog/aftercare-with-eyebeam-icp/ |website=Topical Cream}}</ref>, AdVerse Fest<ref>{{cite web |title=RaFia |url=https://www.redandblack.com/rafia/image_7169489e-3bdb-11e9-810d-5b2e717f3957.html |website=The Red and Black |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>, SleepCenter<ref>{{cite web |title=Home School |url=https://sleepcenterny.org/2017/07/25/home-school/ |website=SleepCenter}}</ref>, Times Square Arts<ref>{{cite web |title=RaFia |url=http://arts.timessquarenyc.org/times-square-arts/artists/rafia/index.aspx |website=Times Square Arts}}</ref>, International Center of Photography<ref>{{cite web |title=9 Art Events to Attend in New York City This Week |url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/9-art-events-attend-new-york-city-week-28-10648/ |website=ARTNews}}</ref>, Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture<ref>{{cite web |last1=Garrett Stodghill |first1=Alexis |title=Harlem artists team up for new Schomburg exhibit honoring the 40th anniversary of Ntozake Shange's poetic monologues |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/manhattan/colored-girls-exhibit-features-harlem-artists-honors-ntozake-shange-work-article-1.1970689 |website=NY Daily News |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Exhibition i found god in myself, Marking the 40th Anniversary of Ntozake Shange\u2019s Seminal Poem, Opens at the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture on Sept. 19 |url=https://www.nypl.org/press/press-release/september-2-2014/new-exhibition-i-found-god-myself-marking-40th-anniversary |website=New York Public Library}}</ref>, Babycastles<ref>{{cite web |title=Multiplay |url=https://www.babycastles.com/master-calendar/multiplay |website=Babycastles |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Museum of the Moving Image<ref>{{cite web |title=INSTALLATION The GIF Elevator |url=http://www.movingimage.us/exhibitions/2017/06/01/detail/the-gif-elevator/ |website=Museum of the Moving Image}}</ref>, and Museum of Contemporary African Disaporan Arts, Roots & Culture <ref>{{cite web |last1=Feliz |first1=Catherine |title=Mutant Dust Bunnies |url=https://www.rootsandculturecac.org/show/dust-bunnies/ |website=Roots & Culture}}</ref> amongst many notable venues. Her work has been featured in publications such as Huffington Post <ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Asha |title=Young Brooklyn artist redefines the selfie in her new show: \"It is not about vanity.\" |url=https://www.salon.com/2015/09/14/young_brooklyn_artist_redefines_the_selfie_in_her_new_show_it_is_not_about_vanity/ |website=Salon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wright |first1=Peter \"Souleo\" |title=On the \u2018A\u2019 w/Souleo: Rafia Santana\u2019s \u2018SELFiE\u2019 Is Better Than Yours |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/on-the-a-wsouleo-rafia-sa_b_7296912 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>, HyperAllergic<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eler |first1=Alicia |title=In Search of the Authentic Selfie |url=https://hyperallergic.com/410585/in-search-of-the-authentic-selfie/ |website=HyperAllergic}}</ref>, Rhizome, ArtFCity<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNamara |first1=Rea |title=GIF of the Day: Rafia Santana\u2019s FREE |url=http://artfcity.com/2015/12/17/gif-of-the-day-rafia-santanas-free/ |website=Art F City}}</ref>, Vogue, Teen Vogue and Salon. She has participated in panels, performances and discussions such as Cultured Magazine<ref>{{cite web |title=AN EVENING WITH TSCHABALALA SELF AND RAFIA |url=https://www.culturedmag.com/rafia/ |website=Cultured |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, \"Late at Tate Britain\"<ref>{{cite web |title=LATE AT TATE BRITAIN: CELEBRITY |url=https://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-britain/late/late-tate-britain-celebrity |website=Tate Britain}}</ref>, Creative Tech Week NYC<ref>{{cite web |title=Rafia Santana |url=https://creativetechweek2016.sched.com/speaker/rafia.1uwju7tu |website=Creative Tech Week |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Afrotectopia at Google NYC<ref>{{cite web |title=Festival at Google NYC August 16 - 18, 2019 |url=https://www.afrotectopia.org/new-gallery/f59vnl6bcni2m8crzzwounytse4k2b |website=Afrotectopia |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, NYU<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Conference |url=https://www.blackportraitures.info/about/ |website=Black Portraiture[s]}}</ref>, \"Black Portraitures IV: The Color of Silence\" at Harvard University and International Center for Photography.<ref>{{cite web |title=DISMANTLING THE GAZE: READING THROUGH MULTIPLY, IDENTIFY, HER |url=https://www.icp.org/events/dismantling-the-gaze-reading-through-multiply-identify-her |website=International Center for Photography |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>Their music is released through Never Normal Records. <ref>{{cite web |title=WATCH THE GO-GO INSPIRED \u201cCRUSH\u201d BY RAFIA |url=http://nevernormalrecords.com/2018/03/watch-go-go-inspired-crush-rafia/ |website=Never Normal Records |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSantana was born and raised in Brooklyn, NY. Coming from a family of creatives where her mother, [[Marilyn Nance]] is a photographer and father a documentary filmmaker, Santana was encouraged to make art as they were growing up.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nedrick, Jr. |first1=Howard |title=PHOTOGRAPHER PROFILE: RAFIA SANTANA |url=http://covealpa.com/2015/02/photographer-rafia-santana/ |website=Cove Alpa |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> They studied photography at Purchase College.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cepeda |first1=Gaby |title=Artist Profile: Rafia Santana |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2016/aug/10/artist-profile-rafia-santana/ |website=Rhizome}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Animated GIFs===\nThroughout her career, Santana has been invited to contribute animated gifs and graphics to online exhibitions and publications such as Body Anxiety<ref>{{cite web |title=Body Anxiety and a new wave of digifeminist art |url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/23717/1/body-anxiety-and-a-new-wave-of-digifeminist-art |website=Dazed Digital}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=RaFiA Santana (info) |url=http://bodyanxiety.com/gallery/rafia-santana/ |website=Body Anxiety}}</ref>, \"Bitrates\" at Shiraz Art House <ref>{{cite web |title=Bitrates |url=http://bitrates.gifbites.com/ |website=Gif Bites}}</ref>. Her gif work has been critically reviewed by The New Inquiry<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dean |first1=Aria |title=Closing the Loop |url=https://thenewinquiry.com/closing-the-loop/ |website=The New Inquiry |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Vice,<ref>{{cite web |title=[Exclusive Preview] 40 Artists Create 'GIFs to Have Sex By' |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/4xq4xg/exclusive-preview-40-artists-create-gifs-to-have-sex-by |website=Vice |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Blavity<ref>{{cite web |title=A Black Feminist Future: How Two Artists Channeled Mary J.Blige's Bold Feminist Statement |url=https://blavity.com/video/a-black-feminist-future-how-two-artists-channeled-mary-jbliges-bold-feminist-statement |website=Blavity |publisher=blklivesmatter}}</ref> and ArtFCity. Of her gif work, Paddy Johnson and Rea McNamara of ArtFCity have opined \" Santana is one of the rare digital artists exploring the vernacular of race, advertising and pop culture.\" <ref>{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Paddy |title=NFSW GIF of the Hump Day: Rafia Santana |url=http://artfcity.com/2017/05/31/nfsw-gif-of-the-hump-day-rafia-santana/ |website=ArtFCity}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McNamara |first1=Rea |title=GIF of the Day: Rafia Santana\u2019s FREE |url=http://artfcity.com/2015/12/17/gif-of-the-day-rafia-santanas-free/ |website=Art F City}}</ref>\n\n====GIF Six-Pack (2016)====\nIn context of Black History Month and Beyonce's release of \"Formation\", Vice columnist invited Santana as one of six artists to contribute gifs that speak out against anti-Blackness and cultural assimilation. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Mufson |first1=Beckett |title=Black GIF Artists Speak Out |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/xy4k5w/black-gif-artist-community |website=Vice}}</ref> Under her gif, RaFia is quoted:\n\u201cPeople of color are underrepresented in every community that white people have ever presented due to the conditioning we\u2019ve received that white is standard. White people are looked at and heard first while POC are represented only if they excel past that standard. Until we\u2019ve abolished the white standard, people of color will always be underrepresented. We\u2019re all here though.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mufson |first1=Beckett |title=Black GIF Artists Speak Out |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/xy4k5w/black-gif-artist-community |website=Vice}}</ref>\n\n===Worked (2015)===\nWorked is a digitally manipulated image of the artist, partially naked with her lower body away from the camera as she gazes forward whilst wearing an apron. It was made with the intention of defying stereotypes around black, femme and queer bodies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Seikaly |first1=Roula |title=Defying Stereotypes, One Post at a Time |url=https://aperture.org/blog/torrent-tea-defying-stereotypes/ |website=Aperture |publisher=Aperture Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sargent |first1=Antwaun |title=Four Artists Explore Black Queer Sexuality on the Internet |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/ezq4gk/four-artists-explore-black-queer-sexuality-on-the-internet |website=The Creators Project |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 'SELFiE' (2015) ===\nIn 2015, Santana mounted a solo show showcasing digitally manipulated images with soundscapes at the Museum of Contemporary African Diasporan Arts.<ref>{{cite web | title=Rafia Santana\u2019s \u2018SELFiE\u2019 Is Better Than Yours |url=https://www.ebony.com/entertainment/rafia-santanas-selfie-is-better-than-yours-403/ |website=Ebony |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Asha |title=Young Brooklyn artist redefines the selfie in her new show: \"It is not about vanity.\" |url=https://www.salon.com/2015/09/14/young_brooklyn_artist_redefines_the_selfie_in_her_new_show_it_is_not_about_vanity/ |website=Salon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wright |first1=Peter \"Souleo\" |title=On the \u2018A\u2019 w/Souleo: Rafia Santana\u2019s \u2018SELFiE\u2019 Is Better Than Yours |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/on-the-a-wsouleo-rafia-sa_b_7296912 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===RaFia's World (2016)===\nCommissioned by a Rhizome Microgrant in 2015, 'RaFia's World' is a static website serving as an archive of written works and drawings from Santana's childhood. <ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2015 Net Art Microgrants |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2015/sep/09/announcing-2015-rhizome-internet-art-microgrants/ |website=Rhizome |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=RaFiA's WORLD |url=https://rafiasworld.com/ |website=RaFiA's WORLD}}</ref> In a profile with Rhizome, Santana tells Cepeda, \"Rafia\u2019s World in its original form exists on my mother's website.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Santana |first1=RaFia |title=This is Rafia's World |url=http://www.marilynnance.com/soulsista/rafia.html |website=Marilyn Nance}}</ref> It is a selection of memories written anecdotally that I illustrated at age six for the purpose of living on my mom\u2019s website as an art piece (my first net art!). It remains there unchanged ten years later. The new RAFiA\u2019s WORLD is a collection of illustrations I made for school assignments and leisure that spans the course of eight years, following my developing consciousness and growth as a kid and artist.\"\n\n===#POWERVHS (2016)===\n\u2018#POWERVHS\u2019<ref>{{cite web |title=#POWERVHS |url=https://vimeo.com/174964173 |website=Vimeo |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> is a 9-artist visual mixtape that Santana compiled to empower black, brown women and queer femme/non-binary artists.<ref>{{cite web |title=#POWERVHS |url=https://www.printedmatter.org/catalog/51139 |website=Printed Matter}}</ref> It features video works by Hattie Ball, Michelle Marie Charles, Angelina Fern\u00e1ndez, Reagan Holiday, Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9, Nandi Loaf, [[Liz Mputu]], [[Sondra Perry]], and Santana herself. The compilation debuted at Disclaimer Gallery on 603 Bushwick Ave, Brooklyn and is available at Printed Matter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Graves |first1=Cassidy Dawn |title=Performance Picks: Harsh Noise Videos IRL, LOL Sadism, and Theatre Ina Garden |url=https://bedfordandbowery.com/2016/08/performance-picks-harsh-noise-videos-irl-lol-sadism-and-theatrical-ina-garden/ |website=Bedford + Bowery}}</ref>\n\n=== #PAYBLACKTIME (2016-Present)===\n\"#PAYBLACKTIME\" is a grassroots initiative started by Santana to collect funds for food delivery through Seamless and Grubhub to marginal individuals who can't afford meals.<ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME |url=https://raf-i-a.tumblr.com/post/153188418768/payblacktime-is-my-white-money-transference |website=RaFiA |publisher=Tumblr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME BY RAFIA SANTANA DEMANDS REIMBURSEMENT FOR BLACK AND BROWN FOLX |url=https://news.feltzine.us/2016/11/16/payblacktime-by-rafia-santana-demands-reimbursement-for-black-and-brown-folx-felt-chat/ |website=felt zine |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> In an interview with Vogue, writer Sandra Song summarizes its goal of turning racial allies' guilt into meaningful action: \"...the #PAYBLACKTiME initiative, which allows the people asking \"Well what can I do to help marginalized folks?\" to manifest their intentions into something tangible \u2014 i.e. food for hungry black and brown people.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Song |first1=Sandra |title=Meet RAFiA Santana, the Multimedia Artist Working GIFs and Grubhub for the Greater Good |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/rafia-santana-fresh-finds |website=Teen Vogue |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> In its first three months, #PAYBLACKTiME transferred over $6,000 in donations into meals purchased.<ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME |url=https://anthology.rhizome.org/payblacktime |website=Net Art Anthology |publisher=Rhizome}}</ref> The work is now archived in Rhizome's Net Art Anthology.<ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME |url=https://anthology.rhizome.org/payblacktime |website=Net Art Anthology |publisher=Rhizome}}</ref>\n\n===re:trospective (2018)===\nAs a parody retrospective of emerging artists curated by maneul abreu, the exhibition featured artworks made by artists of colour in a storefront space located in the gentrified and trendy neighborhood of Bushwick.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallet |first1=Whitney |title=A \u2018Retrospective\u2019 for Emerging Artists in Bushwick\u2019s Former Pfizer Factory |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/a-retrospective-for-emerging-artists-in-bushwick.html |website=Vulture}}</ref> Of Santana's animation, critic Whitney Mallet writes, \"Santana\u2019s video work, which saw digitally rendered faces, including the artist\u2019s and abreu\u2019s, morph and distort.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallet |first1=Whitney |title=A \u2018Retrospective\u2019 for Emerging Artists in Bushwick\u2019s Former Pfizer Factory |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/a-retrospective-for-emerging-artists-in-bushwick.html |website=Vulture}}</ref>\n\n=== Midnight Moment residency (2019) ===\nAs part of Midnight Moment's residency, Santana created a multi-billboard animated video piece that would show for a minute every night for a month in New York in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowling |first1=Suzanna |title=Times Square Arts Presents Their Spring Season Arts Program |url=https://t2conline.com/times-square-arts-presents-their-spring-season-arts-program/ |website=Times Square Chronicles |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowling |first1=Suzanna |title=The Midnight Moment is Dizzillusions |url=https://t2conline.com/the-midnight-moment-is-dizzillusions/ |website=Times Square Chronicles}}</ref> Titled Dizzillusions -the same title as their coterminously released album-the installation featured RaFia's face animated amongst pink and purple backgrounds.\n\n===Dizillusions (2019)===\nDizillusions is a rap and electronic EP released in April 2019 through Never Normal Records.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dizzillusions |url=https://rafia.bandcamp.com/album/dizzillusions |website=Bandcamp}}</ref> Vogue writer Rachel Hahn observed that \"the music video of track \"Ain't Nothin'\" directly references her Times Square installation with lyrics like, \u201cI\u2019m gonna make it big/I\u2019mma see my name in all of them lights.\u201d...which depicts Santana dancing in the middle of Times Square while her animated face takes over the billboards in the background.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hahn |first1=Rachel |title=A Life in Pink: Artist RaFia Santana on Her (Mostly) Magenta Wardrobe |url=https://www.vogue.com/vogueworld/article/rafia-santana-instagram-artist-selfie-pink-wardrobe-dizillusions-aint-nothin-music-video |website=Vogue}}</ref> \n\n<br>\n\n==References==\n{{refList}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santana, RaFia}}\n[[Category:New media artists]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American multimedia artists]]\n[[Category:American video artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:State University of New York at Purchase alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Black American artist and musician}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = RaFia Santana <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| alt = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1990}}\n| birth_place = Brooklyn, NY\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality = American\n| education = SUNY Purchase College\n| alma_mater = [[SUNY Purchase College]]\n| known_for = [[Electronic Music]], [[New Media Art]], [[Performance art ]]\n| notable_works = 'Ain't Nothin', 'Dizzillusionz', 'Worked'\n| style = \n| movement = [[Conceptual art|Conceptual]], [[Internet Art]], [[New Media Art]], [[Postinternet]]\n| spouse = \n| awards = Rhizome MicroGrant, 2015<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2015 Net Art Microgrants |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2015/sep/09/announcing-2015-rhizome-internet-art-microgrants/ |website=Rhizome |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n| elected = \n| patrons = \n| memorials = \n| website = https://raf-i-a.tumblr.com/\n| module = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n\n'''RaFia Santana''' is an African American artist, musician, and performer based in Brooklyn, NY.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cepeda |first1=Gaby |title=Artist Profile: Rafia Santana |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2016/aug/10/artist-profile-rafia-santana/ |website=Rhizome}}</ref> Her work ranges from animated gifs<ref>{{cite web |title=NFSW GIF of the Hump Day: Rafia Santana |url=http://dallasartdealers.org/nfsw-gif-of-the-hump-day-rafia-santana/ |website=Dallas Art Dealers |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> to self-portraiture,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eler |first1=Alicia |title=In Search of the Authentic Selfie |url=https://hyperallergic.com/410585/in-search-of-the-authentic-selfie/ |website=HyperAllergic}}</ref> videos, and performance to editioned clothing and electronic music exploring gentrification, the millennial mindset, mental health, and the lived black experience.<ref>{{cite web |title=RaFia Santana |url=https://www.blackportraitures.info/?person=rafiasantana |website=Black Portraiture[s] |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dizzillusions |url=http://arts.timessquarenyc.org/times-square-arts/projects/midnight-moment/dizzillusions/index.aspx |website=Time Square Arts}}</ref> They use the internet as a medium to share their artwork, empower black and brown communities, and challenge ideas of solidarity and alliance. She had exhibitions and/or performances at the Eyebeam<ref>{{cite web |title=AFTERCARE WITH EYEBEAM + ICP |url=http://topicalcream.info/blog/aftercare-with-eyebeam-icp/ |website=Topical Cream}}</ref>, AdVerse Fest<ref>{{cite web |title=RaFia |url=https://www.redandblack.com/rafia/image_7169489e-3bdb-11e9-810d-5b2e717f3957.html |website=The Red and Black |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>, SleepCenter<ref>{{cite web |title=Home School |url=https://sleepcenterny.org/2017/07/25/home-school/ |website=SleepCenter}}</ref>, Times Square Arts<ref>{{cite web |title=RaFia |url=http://arts.timessquarenyc.org/times-square-arts/artists/rafia/index.aspx |website=Times Square Arts}}</ref>, International Center of Photography<ref>{{cite web |title=9 Art Events to Attend in New York City This Week |url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/9-art-events-attend-new-york-city-week-28-10648/ |website=ARTNews}}</ref>, Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture<ref>{{cite web |last1=Garrett Stodghill |first1=Alexis |title=Harlem artists team up for new Schomburg exhibit honoring the 40th anniversary of Ntozake Shange's poetic monologues |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/manhattan/colored-girls-exhibit-features-harlem-artists-honors-ntozake-shange-work-article-1.1970689 |website=NY Daily News |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Exhibition i found god in myself, Marking the 40th Anniversary of Ntozake Shange\u2019s Seminal Poem, Opens at the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture on Sept. 19 |url=https://www.nypl.org/press/press-release/september-2-2014/new-exhibition-i-found-god-myself-marking-40th-anniversary |website=New York Public Library}}</ref>, Babycastles<ref>{{cite web |title=Multiplay |url=https://www.babycastles.com/master-calendar/multiplay |website=Babycastles |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Museum of the Moving Image<ref>{{cite web |title=INSTALLATION The GIF Elevator |url=http://www.movingimage.us/exhibitions/2017/06/01/detail/the-gif-elevator/ |website=Museum of the Moving Image}}</ref>, and Museum of Contemporary African Disaporan Arts, Roots & Culture <ref>{{cite web |last1=Feliz |first1=Catherine |title=Mutant Dust Bunnies |url=https://www.rootsandculturecac.org/show/dust-bunnies/ |website=Roots & Culture}}</ref> amongst many notable venues. Her work has been featured in publications such as Huffington Post <ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Asha |title=Young Brooklyn artist redefines the selfie in her new show: \"It is not about vanity.\" |url=https://www.salon.com/2015/09/14/young_brooklyn_artist_redefines_the_selfie_in_her_new_show_it_is_not_about_vanity/ |website=Salon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wright |first1=Peter \"Souleo\" |title=On the \u2018A\u2019 w/Souleo: Rafia Santana\u2019s \u2018SELFiE\u2019 Is Better Than Yours |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/on-the-a-wsouleo-rafia-sa_b_7296912 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>, HyperAllergic<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eler |first1=Alicia |title=In Search of the Authentic Selfie |url=https://hyperallergic.com/410585/in-search-of-the-authentic-selfie/ |website=HyperAllergic}}</ref>, Rhizome, ArtFCity<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNamara |first1=Rea |title=GIF of the Day: Rafia Santana\u2019s FREE |url=http://artfcity.com/2015/12/17/gif-of-the-day-rafia-santanas-free/ |website=Art F City}}</ref>, Vogue, Teen Vogue and Salon. She has participated in panels, performances and discussions such as Cultured Magazine<ref>{{cite web |title=AN EVENING WITH TSCHABALALA SELF AND RAFIA |url=https://www.culturedmag.com/rafia/ |website=Cultured |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, \"Late at Tate Britain\"<ref>{{cite web |title=LATE AT TATE BRITAIN: CELEBRITY |url=https://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-britain/late/late-tate-britain-celebrity |website=Tate Britain}}</ref>, Creative Tech Week NYC<ref>{{cite web |title=Rafia Santana |url=https://creativetechweek2016.sched.com/speaker/rafia.1uwju7tu |website=Creative Tech Week |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Afrotectopia at Google NYC<ref>{{cite web |title=Festival at Google NYC August 16 - 18, 2019 |url=https://www.afrotectopia.org/new-gallery/f59vnl6bcni2m8crzzwounytse4k2b |website=Afrotectopia |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, NYU<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Conference |url=https://www.blackportraitures.info/about/ |website=Black Portraiture[s]}}</ref>, \"Black Portraitures IV: The Color of Silence\" at Harvard University and International Center for Photography.<ref>{{cite web |title=DISMANTLING THE GAZE: READING THROUGH MULTIPLY, IDENTIFY, HER |url=https://www.icp.org/events/dismantling-the-gaze-reading-through-multiply-identify-her |website=International Center for Photography |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>Their music is released through Never Normal Records. <ref>{{cite web |title=WATCH THE GO-GO INSPIRED \u201cCRUSH\u201d BY RAFIA |url=http://nevernormalrecords.com/2018/03/watch-go-go-inspired-crush-rafia/ |website=Never Normal Records |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSantana was born and raised in Brooklyn, NY. Coming from a family of creatives where her mother, [[Marilyn Nance]] is a photographer and father a documentary filmmaker, Santana was encouraged to make art as they were growing up.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nedrick, Jr. |first1=Howard |title=PHOTOGRAPHER PROFILE: RAFIA SANTANA |url=http://covealpa.com/2015/02/photographer-rafia-santana/ |website=Cove Alpa |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> They studied photography at Purchase College.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cepeda |first1=Gaby |title=Artist Profile: Rafia Santana |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2016/aug/10/artist-profile-rafia-santana/ |website=Rhizome}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Animated GIFs===\nThroughout her career, Santana has been invited to contribute animated gifs and graphics to online exhibitions and publications such as Body Anxiety<ref>{{cite web |title=Body Anxiety and a new wave of digifeminist art |url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/23717/1/body-anxiety-and-a-new-wave-of-digifeminist-art |website=Dazed Digital}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=RaFiA Santana (info) |url=http://bodyanxiety.com/gallery/rafia-santana/ |website=Body Anxiety}}</ref>, \"Bitrates\" at Shiraz Art House <ref>{{cite web |title=Bitrates |url=http://bitrates.gifbites.com/ |website=Gif Bites}}</ref>. Her gif work has been critically reviewed by The New Inquiry<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dean |first1=Aria |title=Closing the Loop |url=https://thenewinquiry.com/closing-the-loop/ |website=The New Inquiry |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Vice,<ref>{{cite web |title=[Exclusive Preview] 40 Artists Create 'GIFs to Have Sex By' |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/4xq4xg/exclusive-preview-40-artists-create-gifs-to-have-sex-by |website=Vice |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>, Blavity<ref>{{cite web |title=A Black Feminist Future: How Two Artists Channeled Mary J.Blige's Bold Feminist Statement |url=https://blavity.com/video/a-black-feminist-future-how-two-artists-channeled-mary-jbliges-bold-feminist-statement |website=Blavity |publisher=blklivesmatter}}</ref> and ArtFCity. Of her gif work, Paddy Johnson and Rea McNamara of ArtFCity have opined \" Santana is one of the rare digital artists exploring the vernacular of race, advertising and pop culture.\" <ref>{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Paddy |title=NFSW GIF of the Hump Day: Rafia Santana |url=http://artfcity.com/2017/05/31/nfsw-gif-of-the-hump-day-rafia-santana/ |website=ArtFCity}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McNamara |first1=Rea |title=GIF of the Day: Rafia Santana\u2019s FREE |url=http://artfcity.com/2015/12/17/gif-of-the-day-rafia-santanas-free/ |website=Art F City}}</ref>\n\n====GIF Six-Pack (2016)====\nIn context of Black History Month and Beyonce's release of \"Formation\", Vice columnist invited Santana as one of six artists to contribute gifs that speak out against anti-Blackness and cultural assimilation. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Mufson |first1=Beckett |title=Black GIF Artists Speak Out |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/xy4k5w/black-gif-artist-community |website=Vice}}</ref> Under her gif, RaFia is quoted:\n\u201cPeople of color are underrepresented in every community that white people have ever presented due to the conditioning we\u2019ve received that white is standard. White people are looked at and heard first while POC are represented only if they excel past that standard. Until we\u2019ve abolished the white standard, people of color will always be underrepresented. We\u2019re all here though.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mufson |first1=Beckett |title=Black GIF Artists Speak Out |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/xy4k5w/black-gif-artist-community |website=Vice}}</ref>\n\n===Worked (2015)===\nWorked is a digitally manipulated image of the artist, partially naked with her lower body away from the camera as she gazes forward whilst wearing an apron. It was made with the intention of defying stereotypes around black, femme and queer bodies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Seikaly |first1=Roula |title=Defying Stereotypes, One Post at a Time |url=https://aperture.org/blog/torrent-tea-defying-stereotypes/ |website=Aperture |publisher=Aperture Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sargent |first1=Antwaun |title=Four Artists Explore Black Queer Sexuality on the Internet |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/ezq4gk/four-artists-explore-black-queer-sexuality-on-the-internet |website=The Creators Project |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 'SELFiE' (2015) ===\nIn 2015, Santana mounted a solo show showcasing digitally manipulated images with soundscapes at the Museum of Contemporary African Diasporan Arts.<ref>{{cite web | title=Rafia Santana\u2019s \u2018SELFiE\u2019 Is Better Than Yours |url=https://www.ebony.com/entertainment/rafia-santanas-selfie-is-better-than-yours-403/ |website=Ebony |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Asha |title=Young Brooklyn artist redefines the selfie in her new show: \"It is not about vanity.\" |url=https://www.salon.com/2015/09/14/young_brooklyn_artist_redefines_the_selfie_in_her_new_show_it_is_not_about_vanity/ |website=Salon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wright |first1=Peter \"Souleo\" |title=On the \u2018A\u2019 w/Souleo: Rafia Santana\u2019s \u2018SELFiE\u2019 Is Better Than Yours |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/on-the-a-wsouleo-rafia-sa_b_7296912 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===RaFia's World (2016)===\nCommissioned by a Rhizome Microgrant in 2015, 'RaFia's World' is a static website serving as an archive of written works and drawings from Santana's childhood. <ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2015 Net Art Microgrants |url=https://rhizome.org/editorial/2015/sep/09/announcing-2015-rhizome-internet-art-microgrants/ |website=Rhizome |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=RaFiA's WORLD |url=https://rafiasworld.com/ |website=RaFiA's WORLD}}</ref> In a profile with Rhizome, Santana tells Cepeda, \"Rafia\u2019s World in its original form exists on my mother's website.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Santana |first1=RaFia |title=This is Rafia's World |url=http://www.marilynnance.com/soulsista/rafia.html |website=Marilyn Nance}}</ref> It is a selection of memories written anecdotally that I illustrated at age six for the purpose of living on my mom\u2019s website as an art piece (my first net art!). It remains there unchanged ten years later. The new RAFiA\u2019s WORLD is a collection of illustrations I made for school assignments and leisure that spans the course of eight years, following my developing consciousness and growth as a kid and artist.\"\n\n===#POWERVHS (2016)===\n\u2018#POWERVHS\u2019<ref>{{cite web |title=#POWERVHS |url=https://vimeo.com/174964173 |website=Vimeo |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> is a 9-artist visual mixtape that Santana compiled to empower black, brown women and queer femme/non-binary artists.<ref>{{cite web |title=#POWERVHS |url=https://www.printedmatter.org/catalog/51139 |website=Printed Matter}}</ref> It features video works by Hattie Ball, Michelle Marie Charles, Angelina Fern\u00e1ndez, Reagan Holiday, Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9, Nandi Loaf, [[Liz Mputu]], [[Sondra Perry]], and Santana herself. The compilation debuted at Disclaimer Gallery on 603 Bushwick Ave, Brooklyn and is available at Printed Matter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Graves |first1=Cassidy Dawn |title=Performance Picks: Harsh Noise Videos IRL, LOL Sadism, and Theatre Ina Garden |url=https://bedfordandbowery.com/2016/08/performance-picks-harsh-noise-videos-irl-lol-sadism-and-theatrical-ina-garden/ |website=Bedford + Bowery}}</ref>\n\n=== #PAYBLACKTIME (2016-Present)===\n\"#PAYBLACKTIME\" is a grassroots initiative started by Santana to collect funds for food delivery through Seamless and Grubhub to marginal individuals who can't afford meals.<ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME |url=https://raf-i-a.tumblr.com/post/153188418768/payblacktime-is-my-white-money-transference |website=RaFiA |publisher=Tumblr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME BY RAFIA SANTANA DEMANDS REIMBURSEMENT FOR BLACK AND BROWN FOLX |url=https://news.feltzine.us/2016/11/16/payblacktime-by-rafia-santana-demands-reimbursement-for-black-and-brown-folx-felt-chat/ |website=felt zine |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> In an interview with Vogue, writer Sandra Song summarizes its goal of turning racial allies' guilt into meaningful action: \"...the #PAYBLACKTiME initiative, which allows the people asking \"Well what can I do to help marginalized folks?\" to manifest their intentions into something tangible \u2014 i.e. food for hungry black and brown people.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Song |first1=Sandra |title=Meet RAFiA Santana, the Multimedia Artist Working GIFs and Grubhub for the Greater Good |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/rafia-santana-fresh-finds |website=Teen Vogue |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> In its first three months, #PAYBLACKTiME transferred over $6,000 in donations into meals purchased.<ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME |url=https://anthology.rhizome.org/payblacktime |website=Net Art Anthology |publisher=Rhizome}}</ref> The work is now archived in Rhizome's Net Art Anthology.<ref>{{cite web |title=#PAYBLACKTIME |url=https://anthology.rhizome.org/payblacktime |website=Net Art Anthology |publisher=Rhizome}}</ref>\n\n===re:trospective (2018)===\nAs a parody retrospective of emerging artists curated by maneul abreu, the exhibition featured artworks made by artists of colour in a storefront space located in the gentrified and trendy neighborhood of Bushwick.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallet |first1=Whitney |title=A \u2018Retrospective\u2019 for Emerging Artists in Bushwick\u2019s Former Pfizer Factory |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/a-retrospective-for-emerging-artists-in-bushwick.html |website=Vulture}}</ref> Of Santana's animation, critic Whitney Mallet writes, \"Santana\u2019s video work, which saw digitally rendered faces, including the artist\u2019s and abreu\u2019s, morph and distort.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallet |first1=Whitney |title=A \u2018Retrospective\u2019 for Emerging Artists in Bushwick\u2019s Former Pfizer Factory |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/a-retrospective-for-emerging-artists-in-bushwick.html |website=Vulture}}</ref>\n\n=== Midnight Moment residency (2019) ===\nAs part of Midnight Moment's residency, Santana created a multi-billboard animated video piece that would show for a minute every night for a month in New York in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowling |first1=Suzanna |title=Times Square Arts Presents Their Spring Season Arts Program |url=https://t2conline.com/times-square-arts-presents-their-spring-season-arts-program/ |website=Times Square Chronicles |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowling |first1=Suzanna |title=The Midnight Moment is Dizzillusions |url=https://t2conline.com/the-midnight-moment-is-dizzillusions/ |website=Times Square Chronicles}}</ref> Titled Dizzillusions -the same title as their coterminously released album-the installation featured RaFia's face animated amongst pink and purple backgrounds.\n\n===Dizillusions (2019)===\nDizillusions is a rap and electronic EP released in April 2019 through Never Normal Records.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dizzillusions |url=https://rafia.bandcamp.com/album/dizzillusions |website=Bandcamp}}</ref> Vogue writer Rachel Hahn observed that \"the music video of track \"Ain't Nothin'\" directly references her Times Square installation with lyrics like, \u201cI\u2019m gonna make it big/I\u2019mma see my name in all of them lights.\u201d...which depicts Santana dancing in the middle of Times Square while her animated face takes over the billboards in the background.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hahn |first1=Rachel |title=A Life in Pink: Artist RaFia Santana on Her (Mostly) Magenta Wardrobe |url=https://www.vogue.com/vogueworld/article/rafia-santana-instagram-artist-selfie-pink-wardrobe-dizillusions-aint-nothin-music-video |website=Vogue}}</ref> \n\n<br>\n\n==References==\n{{refList}}\n\n[[Category:New media artists]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American multimedia artists]]\n[[Category:American video artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:State University of New York at Purchase alumni]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RaFia_Santana"}
{"title_page": "Annalisa Piras", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:Piras pic.jpg|thumb|Annalisa Piras]]\n\n'''Annalisa Piras ''' is a London-based Italian-British film director, impact producer and journalist. She is currently the director of Springshot Productions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://springshotproductions.com|title=Springshot Production website}}</ref> an independent production company which specialises in documentaries. She also directs The Wake Up Foundation, an educational charity she co-founded with Bill Emmott,former editor of The Economist. In 2019 The Wake Up Foundation founded and run the first Wake Up Europe Impact Films Festival,the first ever transnational impact documentary festival entirely devoted to showcase the best films produced worldwide to highlights the shared challenges our western societies face, with a special focus on the meaning of a European civic conscience. The Wake Up Europe Festival offered a \"selection for reflection\" of 10 films, which were screened and debated in Turin,Italy and across other nine European locations <ref>{{citen web|url=https://www.torinoggi.it/2019/05/18/leggi-notizia/argomenti/eventi-11/articolo/domani-chiude-a-torino-wake-up-europe-festival.html}}</ref>\n\nPiras'2016 film, \"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte]] and [[SVT]] was nominated for the 2016 Prix Europa, the Oscar of European Documentaries. It was broadcast across the world in 2017. The film looks at Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's transnational security challenges and the shifting sands of geopolitics.It gained exclusive access for the first time to the EU top diplomat, the High Representative for Foreign and Security Policies Federica Mogherini. \n\nIn 2015 Annalisa Piras directed \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d, the first ever film on the EU crisis from an international point of view.<ref>''[http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about \"The Great European Disaster Movie - About\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529160739/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about |date=2015-05-29 }}'', thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu, May 29, 2015</ref> It was produced by [[BBC]] and [[Arte]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4288614/|title=IMDB The Great European Disaster Movie}}</ref>\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film was selected among 930 applications from media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in May 2016.\n\n==Career==\n\nAs EU senior editor, Piras was part of the initial team which launched [[Euronews]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3ci3eNe6Dc|title=Youtube-Annalisa Piras-Euronews}}</ref> the pan-European multilingual news television channel, on 1 January 1993 in Lyon, France.\n\nPiras was the London Correspondent for ''[[L'Espresso]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/chi-sono/|title=Annalisa Piras-L'Espresso-chi sono}}</ref>'' from 1997 to 2011 and for La7 TV{{cn|date=January 2020}} for six years. From 2006 to 2007 Annalisa was the first Italian president of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120315000217/http://www.fpalondon.org/showarticle.pl?id=43%3Bn=142%20 London Foreign Press Association].\n\nIn 2008, Piras' BBC Radio 4 documentary [http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml ''The Italian Patient'']<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w0006q6d|title=The Documentary-The Italian Patient}}</ref> was shortlisted as the FPA Best Story of the Year by a UK-based foreign correspondent.  Her TV documentary on the [[Hutton Enquiry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/tag/hutton-inquiry/|title=L'Espresso-Hutton Enquiry}}</ref> written and directed for La7 TV, was shortlisted for the same award in 2003.\n\nIn 2011 and 2012 Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy seen from abroad, [[Girlfriend in a Coma (film)|Girlfriend in a Coma]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> co-written and narrated by [[Bill Emmott]], former editor of ''The Economist'', inspired by his book ''Good Italy, Bad Italy'' (Yale University Press).\n\nPiras collected the 2011 PEN/Pinter prize on behalf of Italian writer, [[Roberto Saviano]], who was unable to attend the ceremony in person because of the failure of the metropolitan police to offer him adequate protection. In addressing Saviano's life under the shadow of Mafia death threats, Piras delivered a speech in honour of his courage, \"with a passion that was raw, exposed and moving\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/oct/14/slovo-pen-prize-roberto-saviano|title=The Guardian: Gillian Slovo: the courage of Roberto Saviano}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Piras founded the Wake Up Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wakeupfoundation.eu|title=The Wake Up Foundation website}}</ref> with the aim to raise public awareness about the current state and decline of the Western Societies through film and storytelling. Through the Wake Up Foundation, Piras and Bill Emmott launched in 2013 the campaign Wake Up Europe! to foster political debate and citizen's participation about the greatest challenges facing Europe. The Wake Up Europe Campaign has since been organising hundreds of documentary screenings and debates across the world, from the Italian Parliament, Montecitorio to a small Town Hall in Denmark or prestigious Universities such as Oxford or Cambridge, the campaign has engaged thousands of citizens fostering informed debates about the future of our societies. \n\nIn 2014 Piras wrote, directed and produced with Bill Emmott the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]] co-produced by Nick Fraser for the BBC Storyville strand, Claudia Bucher, for Arte TV, Axel Arno for SVT, Swedish public Tv.\n\n\"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte|ARTE]] and [[SVT]] and written, produced and directed by Piras followed for two years the footsteps of [[Federica Mogherini]], the High Representative of the European Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy, as she tried to implement the EU Global Strategy, while facing a relentless series of crisis, andunexpected turns, from the vote on Brexit, to the election of President Trump, to the deepening of the refugees and migrants challenge in the South Mediterranean. The film is an unique document to analyses Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's challenges from the perspective of the person called upon to implement a shared European vision, which is sorely elusive.\n\nPiras is a regular member of the BBC ''[[Dateline London]]'' panel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://isthebbcbiased.blogspot.co.uk/2012/11/dateline-guest-of-dishonour.html|title=Dateline Guests}}</ref>\nShe also provided [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa analysis] on European and Italian Current Affairs for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa}}</ref>\n\nAs a political and social commentator she frequently appears on BBC News, Sky News, CNN, Al Jazeera and CNBC.\n\n== Girlfriend in a Coma ==\n{{BLP sources section|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn 2012 Annalisa Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy as seen from abroad, Girlfriend in a Coma,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> working with Bill Emmott, former editor of The Economist, as co-author and narrator.<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2315588/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_2 \"Girlfriend in a Coma\"]'', IMDb, imdb.com, May 29, 2015</ref> The film was made by Springshot Productions.\n\nThe documentary is inspired by Emmott\u2019s book Good Italy, Bad Italy (Yale University Press), as well as by Piras\u2019s patriotic passion and insight about the country she left in the early 1990s.\nThe film aims to introduce Italians and the World to the dark side of the country's political, economic and social decline, the product of a moral collapse in the West. It was broadcast on BBC Four, Sky Italia and La7 TV channels early in 2013, and subsequently on other channels worldwide as well as in public screenings.\n\nThe \u201cGirlfriend in a Coma\u201d title is a citation of a British musical hit by The Smiths from their album Strangeways (1987).\n\n== The Great European Disaster Movie ==\n\nIn 2014 Annalisa Piras wrote, directed and produced with [[Bill Emmott]] the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]]. In an artfully constructed depiction of how Europe is sleepwalking toward disaster, starring Angus Deayton in fiction scenes from a postEU future, the film pairs an imagined view from a dystopian future with insightful, cross national analysis by ordinary Europeans and high level experts on how and why things are going so wrong. Notable interviewees include French economist [[Thomas Piketty]], [[Martin Wolf]], chief economic commentator at the Financial Times, former EU trade commissioner [[Peter Mandelson]], and many former ministers and high level EU officials in various European countries.\n\nIn an authored piece of committed journalism, the filmmakers argue powerfully that, while economic crisis and popular anger are pushing Europe dangerously towards disintegration, the EU is in need of major reform but well worth saving. Subtle, moving, thoughtprovoking and witty, \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d is far more than a political film but instead frames Europe through the eyes of those who are most important to its success: the Europeans themselves.\n\n'''Reception'''\n\nThe Great European Disaster Movie is a BBC/ARTE and 7 other European broadcasters coproduction, which has now been watched by 2.360.000 viewers, one million of which in France and Germany. The film premi\u00e8red on BBC Four, as part of the Storyville strand, on 1 March 2015. It was subsequently broadcast in 12 countries (UK, France, Germany, Switzerland, Austria, Belgium, Italy, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway and Japan) and has been translated in 10 languages, including Japanese.\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d has won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film has been selected among 930 applications by media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in the presence of EU broadcasters yesterday evening May 12.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160514121408/http://www.dw.com/en/civis-media-awards-presented-in-berlin/av-19255971 Watch the video]\n \n'''Controversy'''\n\nThe film generated a great deal of media controversy in the UK, with some critics taking exception at the BBC broadcasting an authored piece with an overtly pro-European slant and others accusing the authors of scaremongering. The BBC broadcast was followed by a live studio debate on Newsnight, the BBC\u2019s news and current affairs programme, during which exec producer Bill Emmott faced several prominent eurosceptic critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|title=The Great European Disaster Movie was meant to stimulate robust debate on Europe's future. What we got was a theological war|work=britishinfluence.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928224214/http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|archivedate=2015-09-28}}</ref>\n\nDirector Annalisa Piras responded to the attacks in a piece for the Guardian and refuted the points more fully on the film\u2019s website in a joint piece with Emmott.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html |title=Nine things The Great European Disaster Movie got wrong |work=telegraph.co.uk/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |title=Nine Things that Toby Young Got Wrong |work=thegreateuropeandiastermovie.eu/ |access-date=2015-09-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929001311/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |archive-date=2015-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBoth Piras and Emmott became the subjects of vitriolic attacks on Twitter by people who argued the film was a piece of \u2018EU propaganda\u2019 despite its strong criticism of the EU institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/mar/05/britain-debate-europe-the-great-european-disaster-movie |title=Is Britain even capable of constructive debate on Europe?|work=theguardian.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n\n\n'''Other Reactions'''\n\nIn his review for The Independent [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/we-could-find-ourselves-back-in-the-europe-of-our-nightmares-10012154.html We could find ourselves back into the Europe of our nightmares.], John Popham called film is a \u201cwake-up call for all those for whom departure from the union could not come a moment too soon and would be the one-stop solution to all our ills, from immigration to health-and-safety nannying\u201d.  The film also received positive coverage in Italy where it was reviewed by [[Il Sole 24]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/commenti-e-idee/2015-04-18/l-europa-filo-disastro-091043_PRN.shtml|title=L'Europa sul filo del disastro|work=ilsole24ore.com/}}</ref> [[Il Fatto Quotidiano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2015/02/15/the-great-european-disaster-movie-la-fidanzata-in-coma-ora-e-leuropa/1426845/  |title=la 'fidanzata in coma' ora \u00e8 l'Europa}}</ref> and [[La Repubblica]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2015/04/17/cera-una-volta-leuropa-unita-la-crisi-in-un-film36.html |title=C'era una volta l'Europa unita la crisi in un film|work=ricerca.repubblica.it/}}</ref> and France. In his review for La Stampa, Brussels Correspondent Marco Zatterin argued that the film unleashed such a \u201cviolent\u201d reaction among British eurosceptics because it \u201cinvaded their territory by criticising Europe but with a view to rebuild it.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2015/03/07/blogs/straneuropa/un-film-contro-il-monopolio-euroscettico-odijJnPxeMkB3lsdxzanUO/pagina.html |title=Un film contro il monopolio euroscettico|work=lastampa.it/}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SU5RCvHSzTM/Backstage Video of \"Girlfriend In a Coma\" Screening at ICA - London]\n* [http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/cultura/2012-12-09/Il riscatto-amica-coma-081838.shtml?uuid=AbgfySAH/ Il riscatto dell'amica in coma. Il Sole 24 Ore]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa/]\n* [http://www.lastampa.it/2012/12/10/societa/l-italia-una-fidanzata-in-coma-XBtP2LdLucrnfW6RevWAxM/pagina.html \"Chi sveglier\u00e0 la ragazza in coma?\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121113073111/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090521012855/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/8044711.stm]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090214234701/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7583739.stm]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HTCuI2d12jQ]\n* [http://wakeupfoundation.eu/ The Wake Up Foundation]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piras, Annalisa}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian journalists]]\n[[Category:Italian film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:Piras pic.jpg|thumb|Annalisa Piras]]\n\n'''Annalisa Piras ''' is a London-based Italian film director, impact producer and journalist. She is currently the director of Springshot Productions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://springshotproductions.com|title=Springshot Production website}}</ref> an independent production company which specialises in documentaries. She also directs The Wake Up Foundation, an educational charity she co-founded with Bill Emmott,former editor of The Economist. In 2019 The Wake Up Foundation founded and run the first Wake Up Europe Impact Films Festival,the first ever transnational impact documentary festival entirely devoted to showcase the best films produced worldwide to highlights the shared challenges our western societies face, with a special focus on the meaning of a European civic conscience. The Wake Up Europe Festival offered a \"selection for reflection\" of 10 films, which were screened and debated in Turin,Italy and across other nine European locations <ref>{{citen web|url=https://www.torinoggi.it/2019/05/18/leggi-notizia/argomenti/eventi-11/articolo/domani-chiude-a-torino-wake-up-europe-festival.html}}</ref>\n\nPiras'2016 film, \"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte]] and [[SVT]] was nominated for the 2016 Prix Europa, the Oscar of European Documentaries. It was broadcast across the world in 2017. The film looks at Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's transnational security challenges and the shifting sands of geopolitics.It gained exclusive access for the first time to the EU top diplomat, the High Representative for Foreign and Security Policies Federica Mogherini. \n\nIn 2015 Annalisa Piras directed \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d, the first ever film on the EU crisis from an international point of view.<ref>''[http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about \"The Great European Disaster Movie - About\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529160739/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about |date=2015-05-29 }}'', thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu, May 29, 2015</ref> It was produced by [[BBC]] and [[Arte]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4288614/|title=IMDB The Great European Disaster Movie}}</ref>\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film was selected among 930 applications from media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in May 2016.\n\n==Career==\n\nAs EU senior editor, Piras was part of the initial team which launched [[Euronews]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3ci3eNe6Dc|title=Youtube-Annalisa Piras-Euronews}}</ref> the pan-European multilingual news television channel, on 1 January 1993 in Lyon, France.\n\nPiras was the London Correspondent for ''[[L'Espresso]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/chi-sono/|title=Annalisa Piras-L'Espresso-chi sono}}</ref>'' from 1997 to 2011 and for La7 TV{{cn|date=January 2020}} for six years. From 2006 to 2007 Annalisa was the first Italian president of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120315000217/http://www.fpalondon.org/showarticle.pl?id=43%3Bn=142%20 London Foreign Press Association].\n\nIn 2008, Piras' BBC Radio 4 documentary [http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml ''The Italian Patient'']<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w0006q6d|title=The Documentary-The Italian Patient}}</ref> was shortlisted as the FPA Best Story of the Year by a UK-based foreign correspondent.  Her TV documentary on the [[Hutton Enquiry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/tag/hutton-inquiry/|title=L'Espresso-Hutton Enquiry}}</ref> written and directed for La7 TV, was shortlisted for the same award in 2003.\n\nIn 2011 and 2012 Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy seen from abroad, [[Girlfriend in a Coma (film)|Girlfriend in a Coma]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> co-written and narrated by [[Bill Emmott]], former editor of ''The Economist'', inspired by his book ''Good Italy, Bad Italy'' (Yale University Press).\n\nPiras collected the 2011 PEN/Pinter prize on behalf of Italian writer, [[Roberto Saviano]], who was unable to attend the ceremony in person because of the failure of the metropolitan police to offer him adequate protection. In addressing Saviano's life under the shadow of Mafia death threats, Piras delivered a speech in honour of his courage, \"with a passion that was raw, exposed and moving\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/oct/14/slovo-pen-prize-roberto-saviano|title=The Guardian: Gillian Slovo: the courage of Roberto Saviano}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Piras founded the Wake Up Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wakeupfoundation.eu|title=The Wake Up Foundation website}}</ref> with the aim to raise public awareness about the current state and decline of the Western Societies through film and storytelling. Through the Wake Up Foundation, Piras and Bill Emmott launched in 2013 the campaign Wake Up Europe! to foster political debate and citizen's participation about the greatest challenges facing Europe. The Wake Up Europe Campaign has since been organising hundreds of documentary screenings and debates across the world, from the Italian Parliament, Montecitorio to a small Town Hall in Denmark or prestigious Universities such as Oxford or Cambridge, the campaign has engaged thousands of citizens fostering informed debates about the future of our societies. \n\nIn 2014 Piras wrote, directed and produced with Bill Emmott the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]] co-produced by Nick Fraser for the BBC Storyville strand, Claudia Bucher, for Arte TV, Axel Arno for SVT, Swedish public Tv.\n\n\"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte|ARTE]] and [[SVT]] and written, produced and directed by Piras followed for two years the footsteps of [[Federica Mogherini]], the High Representative of the European Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy, as she tried to implement the EU Global Strategy, while facing a relentless series of crisis, andunexpected turns, from the vote on Brexit, to the election of President Trump, to the deepening of the refugees and migrants challenge in the South Mediterranean. The film is an unique document to analyses Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's challenges from the perspective of the person called upon to implement a shared European vision, which is sorely elusive.\n\nPiras is a regular member of the BBC ''[[Dateline London]]'' panel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://isthebbcbiased.blogspot.co.uk/2012/11/dateline-guest-of-dishonour.html|title=Dateline Guests}}</ref>\nShe also provided [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa analysis] on European and Italian Current Affairs for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa}}</ref>\n\nAs a political and social commentator she frequently appears on BBC News, Sky News, CNN, Al Jazeera and CNBC.\n\n== Girlfriend in a Coma ==\n{{BLP sources section|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn 2012 Annalisa Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy as seen from abroad, Girlfriend in a Coma,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> working with Bill Emmott, former editor of The Economist, as co-author and narrator.<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2315588/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_2 \"Girlfriend in a Coma\"]'', IMDb, imdb.com, May 29, 2015</ref> The film was made by Springshot Productions.\n\nThe documentary is inspired by Emmott\u2019s book Good Italy, Bad Italy (Yale University Press), as well as by Piras\u2019s patriotic passion and insight about the country she left in the early 1990s.\nThe film aims to introduce Italians and the World to the dark side of the country's political, economic and social decline, the product of a moral collapse in the West. It was broadcast on BBC Four, Sky Italia and La7 TV channels early in 2013, and subsequently on other channels worldwide as well as in public screenings.\n\nThe \u201cGirlfriend in a Coma\u201d title is a citation of a British musical hit by The Smiths from their album Strangeways (1987).\n\n== The Great European Disaster Movie ==\n\nIn 2014 Annalisa Piras wrote, directed and produced with [[Bill Emmott]] the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]]. In an artfully constructed depiction of how Europe is sleepwalking toward disaster, starring Angus Deayton in fiction scenes from a postEU future, the film pairs an imagined view from a dystopian future with insightful, cross national analysis by ordinary Europeans and high level experts on how and why things are going so wrong. Notable interviewees include French economist [[Thomas Piketty]], [[Martin Wolf]], chief economic commentator at the Financial Times, former EU trade commissioner [[Peter Mandelson]], and many former ministers and high level EU officials in various European countries.\n\nIn an authored piece of committed journalism, the filmmakers argue powerfully that, while economic crisis and popular anger are pushing Europe dangerously towards disintegration, the EU is in need of major reform but well worth saving. Subtle, moving, thoughtprovoking and witty, \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d is far more than a political film but instead frames Europe through the eyes of those who are most important to its success: the Europeans themselves.\n\n'''Reception'''\n\nThe Great European Disaster Movie is a BBC/ARTE and 7 other European broadcasters coproduction, which has now been watched by 2.360.000 viewers, one million of which in France and Germany. The film premi\u00e8red on BBC Four, as part of the Storyville strand, on 1 March 2015. It was subsequently broadcast in 12 countries (UK, France, Germany, Switzerland, Austria, Belgium, Italy, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway and Japan) and has been translated in 10 languages, including Japanese.\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d has won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film has been selected among 930 applications by media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in the presence of EU broadcasters yesterday evening May 12.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160514121408/http://www.dw.com/en/civis-media-awards-presented-in-berlin/av-19255971 Watch the video]\n \n'''Controversy'''\n\nThe film generated a great deal of media controversy in the UK, with some critics taking exception at the BBC broadcasting an authored piece with an overtly pro-European slant and others accusing the authors of scaremongering. The BBC broadcast was followed by a live studio debate on Newsnight, the BBC\u2019s news and current affairs programme, during which exec producer Bill Emmott faced several prominent eurosceptic critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|title=The Great European Disaster Movie was meant to stimulate robust debate on Europe's future. What we got was a theological war|work=britishinfluence.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928224214/http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|archivedate=2015-09-28}}</ref>\n\nDirector Annalisa Piras responded to the attacks in a piece for the Guardian and refuted the points more fully on the film\u2019s website in a joint piece with Emmott.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html |title=Nine things The Great European Disaster Movie got wrong |work=telegraph.co.uk/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |title=Nine Things that Toby Young Got Wrong |work=thegreateuropeandiastermovie.eu/ |access-date=2015-09-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929001311/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |archive-date=2015-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBoth Piras and Emmott became the subjects of vitriolic attacks on Twitter by people who argued the film was a piece of \u2018EU propaganda\u2019 despite its strong criticism of the EU institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/mar/05/britain-debate-europe-the-great-european-disaster-movie |title=Is Britain even capable of constructive debate on Europe?|work=theguardian.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n\n\n'''Other Reactions'''\n\nIn his review for The Independent [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/we-could-find-ourselves-back-in-the-europe-of-our-nightmares-10012154.html We could find ourselves back into the Europe of our nightmares.], John Popham called film is a \u201cwake-up call for all those for whom departure from the union could not come a moment too soon and would be the one-stop solution to all our ills, from immigration to health-and-safety nannying\u201d.  The film also received positive coverage in Italy where it was reviewed by [[Il Sole 24]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/commenti-e-idee/2015-04-18/l-europa-filo-disastro-091043_PRN.shtml|title=L'Europa sul filo del disastro|work=ilsole24ore.com/}}</ref> [[Il Fatto Quotidiano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2015/02/15/the-great-european-disaster-movie-la-fidanzata-in-coma-ora-e-leuropa/1426845/  |title=la 'fidanzata in coma' ora \u00e8 l'Europa}}</ref> and [[La Repubblica]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2015/04/17/cera-una-volta-leuropa-unita-la-crisi-in-un-film36.html |title=C'era una volta l'Europa unita la crisi in un film|work=ricerca.repubblica.it/}}</ref> and France. In his review for La Stampa, Brussels Correspondent Marco Zatterin argued that the film unleashed such a \u201cviolent\u201d reaction among British eurosceptics because it \u201cinvaded their territory by criticising Europe but with a view to rebuild it.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2015/03/07/blogs/straneuropa/un-film-contro-il-monopolio-euroscettico-odijJnPxeMkB3lsdxzanUO/pagina.html |title=Un film contro il monopolio euroscettico|work=lastampa.it/}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SU5RCvHSzTM/Backstage Video of \"Girlfriend In a Coma\" Screening at ICA - London]\n* [http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/cultura/2012-12-09/Il riscatto-amica-coma-081838.shtml?uuid=AbgfySAH/ Il riscatto dell'amica in coma. Il Sole 24 Ore]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa/]\n* [http://www.lastampa.it/2012/12/10/societa/l-italia-una-fidanzata-in-coma-XBtP2LdLucrnfW6RevWAxM/pagina.html \"Chi sveglier\u00e0 la ragazza in coma?\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121113073111/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090521012855/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/8044711.stm]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090214234701/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7583739.stm]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HTCuI2d12jQ]\n* [http://wakeupfoundation.eu/ The Wake Up Foundation]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piras, Annalisa}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian journalists]]\n[[Category:Italian film directors]]\n", "name_user": "Urban-stories", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annalisa_Piras"}
{"title_page": "Jennifer Guglielmo", "text_new": "'''Jennifer Guglielmo''' is a [[List of Italian American Women Writers|writer]], historian and associate professor at [[Smith College]],<ref name=Associate>{{Cite web |url=http://smith.edu/history/faculty_guglielmo.php |title=History Faculty, Jennifer Guglielmo. |access-date=2012-07-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002055840/http://www.smith.edu/history/faculty_guglielmo.php |archive-date=2012-10-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> specializing in the histories of labor, race, women, im/migration, transnational cultures and activisms, and revolutionary social movements in the modern United States. She has published on a range of topics, including working-class feminisms, anarchism, whiteness and the Italian diaspora.\n\nGuglielmo is the author of the award-winning book ''Living the Revolution: Italian Women's Resistance and Radicalism in New York City, 1880\u20131945'' (2010)<ref name=Guglielmo>Jennifer Guglielmo, ''Living the Revolution: Italian Women's Resistance and Radicalism in New York City, 1880-1945.'' Chapel Hill: [[University of North Carolina Press]] (Gender and American Culture Series), 2010.</ref> and co-editor (with Salvatore Salerno) of ''Are Italians White? How Race Is Made in America'' (2003).<ref name=GuglielmoTwo>Jennifer Guglielmo, ''Are Italians White? How Race Is Made in America.'' New York: [[Routledge]], 2003.</ref> The book was translated into Italian in 2006: ''Gli Italiani Sono Bianchi? Come l' America ha costruito la razza.''.<ref name=GuglielmoThree>Jennifer Guglielmo, ''Gli Italiani Sono Bianchi? Come l'America ha costruito la razza.'' Milan: Il Saggiatore Press, 2006.</ref> She is currently translating short essays written in Italian by immigrant women [[Anarcha-feminism|anarchists]]\u2014such as [[Maria Roda]] and [[Virgilia D'Andrea]]\u2014in early twentieth-century New York City and northeastern New Jersey.<ref name=Gold>Susannah Gold, [http://www.i-italy.org/15577/italian-working-class-women-us-start-20th-century \"Italian Working-Class Women in the US at the Start of the 20th Century.\"] i-Italy.org, October 5, 2010.</ref> These will be reprinted in her next book, ''My Rebellious Heart: Immigrant Women's Anarchist Feminist Prose in New York City's Radical Subculture, 1890\u20131930.''\n\nGuglielmo is also currently engaged in a grant-funded, collaborative, community-based public history/digital humanities project with the [[National Domestic Workers Alliance]]. Together they are developing tools for domestic workers and organizers to access historical knowledge and archival evidence and use history as an organizing tool.\n\n==Life and family==\nJennifer Guglielmo was born in Flushing, NY. \n\n==Education and career==\nGuglielmo received a Bachelor of Arts in history and women's studies from [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] in 1990, a Masters of Arts in history from [[University of New Mexico]] in 1995 and a PhD in history from [[University of Minnesota]] in 2003. Her doctoral dissertation, \"Negotiating Gender, Race and Coalition: Italian Women and Working-Class Politics in New York City, 1880 to 1945\", won the Best Dissertation Award<ref name=Best>[http://www.ihrc.umn.edu/whoweare/newsJul19-04.php Jennifer Guglielmo wins Best Dissertation Award.]</ref> from the [[University of Minnesota]] and the [[Organization of American Historians]]\u2019 Lerner-Scott Prize<ref name=Lerner>[http://www.oah.org/awards/awards.lernerscott.winners.html Lerner-Scott Winners], 2004.</ref> for best doctoral dissertation in U.S. women\u2019s history.\n\nShe taught history and women's studies at [[William Paterson University]], [[SUNY New Paltz]], [[Ulster County Community College]], and the [[University of Minnesota]], before joining the faculty at [[Smith College]] in 2003.\n\n==Honors and awards==\n*[[Smith College]] Sherrerd Prize for Distinguished Teaching, 2012.<ref name=Sherrerd>[http://www.smith.edu/events/sherrerd_2012.php 2012 Recipients.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520111822/http://www.smith.edu/events/sherrerd_2012.php |date=2012-05-20 }}</ref>\n*Helen and [[Howard R. Marraro]] Book Award<ref name=MarraroOne>[http://www.historians.org/prizes/index.cfm?PrizeAbbrev=Marraro The Helen & Howard R. Marraro Prize]</ref> for ''Living the Revolution,'' 2011.<ref name=Marraro>Helen and Howard R. Marraro Book Award, [http://www.italianhistoricalstudies.org/marraro.html List of Recipients] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404102128/http://www.italianhistoricalstudies.org/marraro.html |date=2012-04-04 }}, Society for Italian Historical Studies and the American Historical Association, 2011.</ref>\n*[[Theodore Saloutos]] Memorial Award for Best Book in U.S. Immigration History, ''Living the Revolution,'' 2010.<ref name=Theodore>Immigration and Ethnic History Society, [https://archive.today/20130415063538/http://www.iehs.org/awards_winners.php?PHPSESSID=581b6ea95a4e47f6ea91dfca0d35fdfe 2010 Theodore Saloutos Memorial Award Winners], 2010.</ref>\n*Honorable Mention from the [[Berkshire Conference of Women Historians]]<ref name=Berk>[http://berksconference.org Berkshire Conference of Women Historians.]</ref> for Best First Book, ''Living the Revolution,'' 2010.<ref name=Berkshire>Berkshire Conference of Women Historians, [http://berksconference.org/prizes-and-awards/2010-winners-of-the-berks-book-and-article-prizes Jennifer Guglielmo's ''Living the Revolution,'' Honorable Mention Best First Book] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103235558/http://berksconference.org/prizes-and-awards/2010-winners-of-the-berks-book-and-article-prizes/ |date=2013-01-03 }}, 2010.</ref>\n*[[Organization of American Historians]] Lerner-Scott Prize for the Best Doctoral Dissertation in U.S. Women's History, 2004.<ref name=\"Lerner\"/>\n*[[University of Minnesota]] Best Dissertation Award for \"Negotiating Gender, Race and Coalition: Italian Women and Working Politics in New York City, 1880 to 1945,\u201d 2003.<ref name=\"Best\"/>\n\n==Grants and fellowships==\nIn 2018, Guglielmo and Michelle Joffroy (Smith College) received a private grant of over $2 million for a three-year public history/worker education project (2018-2021) with the [[National Domestic Workers Alliance]]. Guglielmo's work has also been funded by the [[Social Science Research Council]] and the [[American Association of University Women]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guglielmo, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Social historians]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:University of New Mexico alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota alumni]]\n[[Category:Smith College faculty]]\n[[Category:American women historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Jennifer Guglielmo''' is a [[List of Italian American Women Writers|writer]], historian and associate professor at [[Smith College]],<ref name=Associate>{{Cite web |url=http://smith.edu/history/faculty_guglielmo.php |title=History Faculty, Jennifer Guglielmo. |access-date=2012-07-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002055840/http://www.smith.edu/history/faculty_guglielmo.php |archive-date=2012-10-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> specializing in the histories of labor, race, women, im/migration, transnational cultures and activisms, and revolutionary social movements in the modern United States. She has published on a range of topics, including working-class feminisms, anarchism, whiteness and the Italian diaspora.\n\nGuglielmo is the author of the award-winning book ''Living the Revolution: Italian Women's Resistance and Radicalism in New York City, 1880-1945'' (2010)<ref name=Guglielmo>Jennifer Guglielmo, ''Living the Revolution: Italian Women's Resistance and Radicalism in New York City, 1880-1945.'' Chapel Hill: [[University of North Carolina Press]] (Gender and American Culture Series), 2010.</ref> and co-editor (with Salvatore Salerno) of ''Are Italians White? How Race Is Made in America'' (2003).<ref name=GuglielmoTwo>Jennifer Guglielmo, ''Are Italians White? How Race Is Made in America.'' New York: [[Routledge]], 2003.</ref> The book was translated into Italian in 2006: ''Gli Italiani Sono Bianchi? Come l' America ha costruito la razza.''.<ref name=GuglielmoThree>Jennifer Guglielmo, ''Gli Italiani Sono Bianchi? Come l'America ha costruito la razza.'' Milan: Il Saggiatore Press, 2006.</ref> She is currently translating short essays written in Italian by immigrant women [[Anarcha-feminism|anarchists]]\u2014such as [[Maria Roda]] and [[Virgilia D'Andrea]]\u2014in early twentieth-century New York City and northeastern New Jersey.<ref name=Gold>Susannah Gold, [http://www.i-italy.org/15577/italian-working-class-women-us-start-20th-century \"Italian Working-Class Women in the US at the Start of the 20th Century.\"] i-Italy.org, October 5, 2010.</ref> These will be reprinted in her next book, ''My Rebellious Heart: Immigrant Women's Anarchist Feminist Prose in New York City's Radical Subculture, 1890-1930.''\n\nGuglielmo is also currently engaged in a grant-funded, collaborative, community-based public history/digital humanities project with the [[National Domestic Workers Alliance]]. Together they are developing tools for domestic workers and organizers to access historical knowledge and archival evidence and use history as an organizing tool.\n\n==Life & Family==\nJennifer Guglielmo was born in Flushing, NY. \n\n==Education & Career==\nGuglielmo received a Bachelor of Arts in History and Women's Studies from [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] in 1990, a Masters of Arts in History from [[University of New Mexico]] in 1995 and a PhD in History from [[University of Minnesota]] in 2003. Her doctoral dissertation, \u201cNegotiating Gender, Race and Coalition: Italian Women and Working-Class Politics in New York City, 1880 to 1945\u201d won the Best Dissertation Award<ref name=Best>[http://www.ihrc.umn.edu/whoweare/newsJul19-04.php Jennifer Guglielmo wins Best Dissertation Award.]</ref> from the [[University of Minnesota]] and the [[Organization of American Historians]]\u2019 Lerner-Scott Prize<ref name=Lerner>[http://www.oah.org/awards/awards.lernerscott.winners.html Lerner-Scott Winners], 2004.</ref> for best doctoral dissertation in U.S. women\u2019s history.\n\nShe taught History and Women's Studies at [[William Paterson University]], [[SUNY New Paltz]], [[Ulster County Community College]], and the [[University of Minnesota]], before joining the faculty at [[Smith College]] in 2003.\n\n==Honors & Awards==\n*[[Smith College]] Sherrerd Prize for Distinguished Teaching, 2012.<ref name=Sherrerd>[http://www.smith.edu/events/sherrerd_2012.php 2012 Recipients.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520111822/http://www.smith.edu/events/sherrerd_2012.php |date=2012-05-20 }}</ref>\n*Helen and [[Howard R. Marraro]] Book Award<ref name=MarraroOne>[http://www.historians.org/prizes/index.cfm?PrizeAbbrev=Marraro The Helen & Howard R. Marraro Prize]</ref> for ''Living the Revolution,'' 2011.<ref name=Marraro>Helen and Howard R. Marraro Book Award, [http://www.italianhistoricalstudies.org/marraro.html List of Recipients] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404102128/http://www.italianhistoricalstudies.org/marraro.html |date=2012-04-04 }}, Society for Italian Historical Studies and the American Historical Association, 2011.</ref>\n*[[Theodore Saloutos]] Memorial Award for Best Book in U.S. Immigration History, ''Living the Revolution,'' 2010.<ref name=Theodore>Immigration and Ethnic History Society, [https://archive.today/20130415063538/http://www.iehs.org/awards_winners.php?PHPSESSID=581b6ea95a4e47f6ea91dfca0d35fdfe 2010 Theodore Saloutos Memorial Award Winners], 2010.</ref>\n*Honorable Mention from the [[Berkshire Conference of Women Historians]]<ref name=Berk>[http://berksconference.org Berkshire Conference of Women Historians.]</ref> for Best First Book, ''Living the Revolution,'' 2010.<ref name=Berkshire>Berkshire Conference of Women Historians, [http://berksconference.org/prizes-and-awards/2010-winners-of-the-berks-book-and-article-prizes Jennifer Guglielmo's ''Living the Revolution,'' Honorable Mention Best First Book] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103235558/http://berksconference.org/prizes-and-awards/2010-winners-of-the-berks-book-and-article-prizes/ |date=2013-01-03 }}, 2010.</ref>\n*[[Organization of American Historians]] Lerner-Scott Prize for the Best Doctoral Dissertation in U.S. Women's History, 2004.<ref name=\"Lerner\"/>\n*[[University of Minnesota]] Best Dissertation Award for \"Negotiating Gender, Race and Coalition: Italian Women and Working Politics in New York City, 1880 to 1945,\u201d 2003.<ref name=\"Best\"/>\n\n==Grants & Fellowships==\nIn 2018, Guglielmo and Michelle Joffroy (Smith College) received a private grant of over $2 million for a three-year public history/worker education project (2018-2021) with the [[National Domestic Workers Alliance]]. Guglielmo's work has also been funded by the [[Social Science Research Council]] and the [[American Association of University Women]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guglielmo, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Social historians]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:University of New Mexico alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota alumni]]\n[[Category:Smith College faculty]]\n[[Category:American women historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: 1880-1945 \u2192 1880\u20131945 (2),  & Awards \u2192  and awards,  & Career \u2192  and career,  & Family \u2192  and family, etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jennifer_Guglielmo"}
{"title_page": "Whitestone Branch", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|former Long Island Rail Road branch}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Whitestone Branch\n|image       = Whitestone LIRR ferry site jeh.jpg\n|image_width =300px\n|caption     = Beechhurst Yacht Club, the site of the former northern terminus of the Whitestone Branch\n|type        = Passenger and Freight\n|system      = \n|status      = Abandoned\n|locale      = [[Queens, New York City]]\n|start       = [[Willets Point, Queens|Willets Point]] (south)\n|end         = [[Whitestone, Queens|Whitestone]] (north)\n|stations    = 5\n|routes      = \n|daily_ridership = \n|open        = {{Start date|1869}}\n|close       = {{End date|1932|2|19}}\n|owner       = \n|operator    = [[Flushing and North Side Railroad]]<br>[[Long Island Rail Road]]\n|character   = \n|stock       = \n|linelength  = \n|tracklength = \n|tracks = 1\u20132\n|gauge       = {{RailGauge|4ft8.5in}}\n|electrification = 1912<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trainsarefun.com/lirr/branchnotes.htm#Whitestone|title=LIRR Branch Notes|work=trainsarefun.com}}</ref>\n|speed       = \n|elevation   = \n|map         = \n}}\nThe '''Whitestone Branch''' was a branch of the [[Long Island Rail Road]], running north and east along the left bank of the [[Flushing River]] from the [[Port Washington Branch]] near the modern [[Willets Point, Queens|Willets Point]]/[[Flushing, Queens|Flushing]] sections of [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]].  It crossed the river on one of the three bridges that were later torn down for the [[Interstate 678|Van Wyck Expressway]], then ran north along [[Flushing Bay]] and east along the East River to [[Whitestone, Queens|Whitestone]].\n\n==History==\nOriginally conceived as a branch of the [[Flushing and North Side Railroad]] that was intended to lead into [[Westchester County, New York]] (a connection that never materialized) in 1869, it was consolidated into the Long Island Rail Road in 1876 when its owners, the Poppenhusen family, took over the bankrupt LIRR. It later became part of a subsidiary called the [[Long Island City and Flushing Railroad]].\n\nOn October 12, 1912 the branch was electrified.<ref>[http://www.lirrhistory.com/mar2009/WhitestoneLIRR.pdf Electric Trains to Whitestone October 22]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lirrhistory.com/whistone.html|title=Whitestone Branch of LIRR|work=lirrhistory.com}}</ref> In the 1920s the branch began to lose patronage and the LIRR sought to rid itself of the line. There was a proposal for the city-owned [[Independent Subway System]] to buy the line and [[IND Second System|incorporate it]] into the [[New York City Subway]] system. The deal was not successful, most likely due to the numerous [[grade crossing]]s that would have been extremely costly to remove. The [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] allowed the LIRR to abandon the line in 1932.<!--Prior to this, the LIRR built the [[Corona Meadows Team Yard]] along the west side of the tracks north of Whitestone Junction along the Port Washington Branch.<ref>[http://arrts-arrchives.com/cmfrt.html Corona Meadows Yard and Bridge Street Drawbridge (Arrt's Arrchives)]</ref>-->\n\nMost of the branch was removed, except a small section of the line leading to the [[Corona Yard]] which remained well into the 1970s when the LIRR closed the Corona Yard and turned it over to the [[New York City Transit Authority]] for [[New York City Subway|subway]] use. Today only a small section of track remains just east of [[Mets\u2013Willets Point station (LIRR)|Mets\u2013Willets Point station]], branching off from the Port Washington Branch east of the station. The [[Flushing\u2013Main Street station (LIRR)|Flushing\u2013Main Street station]] of the [[Port Washington Branch]] was so named to distinguish it from the Whitestone's Flushing\u2013Bridge Street station. Despite the closing of the Bridge Street station, the LIRR continues to use the name \"Main Street\" for the Port Washington Branch station to this day.\n\nA spur of the line near the Flushing River was abandoned when it went under water in 1983. Private homes have been built over the section of the line in Whitestone Landing.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite book|title=An Assessment of the Transit Service Potential of Inactive Railroad Rights-of-way and Yards Final Report|last=|first=|date=October 1991|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\n==Flushing Bay Freight Spur==\nThe Flushing Bay Freight Spur was a freight-only spur that lead to a freight dock on [[Flushing Bay]] just west of the [[Flushing River]] delta. It began at the Whitestone Branch just north of the junction with the Port Washington Branch, then crossed a junction with a spur of the [[Woodside Branch]] leading to Great Neck Junction and the [[Central Branch (Long Island Rail Road)|Central Branch]], and a second junction with Woodside Branch that lead to the Whitestone Branch,{{refn|1=Seyfried, Vincent F. [[:wikisource:The Long Island Rail Road: A Comprehensive History, Part Two: The Flushing, North Shore & Central Railroad|\"The Long Island Rail Road: A Comprehensive History, Part Two: The Flushing, North Shore & Central Railroad\"]] (1961). \"There were in addition two branches: the four mile spur to Whitestone and a shorter one of one and one quarter miles to Hempstead. The Flushing Creek area was the throat of the system with two main junction points: Whitestone Junction on the west side, where the Whitestone Branch began, and Central Junction on the east bank, where the Central trains turned off for Babylon. When the Woodside Branch opened in April 1874, four more miles of single track were added, plus an additional trestle bridge and connecting spur from Central Junction to the Flushing Bay dock.\"}} and crossing a short bridge before finally terminating at the freight dock. No trace of the spur is known {{as of|2016|lc=yes}}.\n\n==Stations==\nThe entire line was abandoned on February 15, 1932.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Miles from Long Island City\n!Station\n!Date<br>opened\n!Date<br>closed\n!Connections&nbsp;/ notes\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|''[[Port Washington Branch]] diverges''\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|''Junction with [[Flushing Bay Freight Spur]]''\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|''[[Woodside Branch]] diverges''\n|-\n|7.9<ref name=\"flickr.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/20489882171/in/dateposted/|title=$_57-11|work=Flickr - Photo Sharing!}}</ref>\n|[[Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Bridge Street (LIRR station)|Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Bridge Street]]\n|1870\n|1932\n|Named to distinguish it from [[Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Main Street (LIRR station)|Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Main Street]] station\n|-\n|9.3<ref name=\"flickr.com\"/>\n|[[College Point (LIRR station)|College Point]]\n|1868<ref name=\"cprazed\">{{cite news |title=College Point Station Razed as 'Eyesore' |url=http://www.fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2014/Jamaica%20NY%20Long%20Island%20Daily%20Press/Jamaica%20NY%20Long%20Island%20Daily%20Press%201934/Jamaica%20NY%20Long%20Island%20Daily%20Press%201934%20-%205339.pdf |accessdate=March 14, 2019 |work=The Press Service Page |date=September 21, 1934 |page=1}}</ref>\n|1932\n|The station depot was razed in September 1934 after local complaints of its deterioration.<ref name=\"cprazed\" />\n|-\n|10.3<ref name=\"flickr.com\"/>\n|[[Malba (LIRR station)|Malba]]\n|1909<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112089483272;view=1up;seq=80|title=The Long Island Railroad Twenty-Seventh Annual Report For The Year Ending December 31st, 1908|last=|first=|publisher=Long Island Railroad Company|year=1909|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Rp|19}}\n|1932\n|Only station on the line built by LIRR<br>At the beginning of its operation, it was a flag stop<ref name=\"flickr.com\"/>\n|-\n|11.0<ref name=\"flickr.com\"/>\n|[[Whitestone&nbsp;\u2013 14th Avenue (LIRR station)|Whitestone&nbsp;\u2013 14th Avenue]]\n|1869\n|1932\n|[[Whitestone Line (NY&NST surface)|Whitestone Trolley]]\n|-\n|11.7<ref name=\"flickr.com\"/>\n|[[Whitestone Landing (LIRR station)|Whitestone Landing]]\n|1886\n|1932\n|Originally [[Beechhurst Yacht Club Station (LIRR station)|Beechhurst Yacht Club Station]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lirrhistory.com/whistone.html Whitestone Branch] (Unofficial LIRR History Website)\n*[http://forgotten-ny.com/2001/10/like-a-rolling-whitestone/ Like a Rolling Whitestone] (ForgottenNY.com)\n*[http://arrts-arrchives.com/wstone1.html Whitestone Branch Part One], [http://arrts-arrchives.com/cmfrt.html Part Two], [http://arrts-arrchives.com/wstbrp3.html Part Three], [http://arrts-arrchives.com/wstone2r.html Part Four], and [http://arrts-arrchives.com/wstone3.html Part Five (Arrt's Arrchives)]\n* [https://placesnomore.wordpress.com/2015/01/23/tracing-out-the-lirr-whitestone-branch/ Tracing Out The LIRR Whitestone Branch (LI & NY Places that are no more)]\n\n{{Long Island Rail Road}}\n\n[[Category:Long Island Rail Road branches]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1869]]\n[[Category:Railway lines closed in 1932]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Whitestone Branch\n|image       = Whitestone LIRR ferry site jeh.jpg\n|image_width =300px\n|caption     = Beechhurst Yacht Club, the site of the former northern terminus of the Whitestone Branch\n|type        = Passenger and Freight\n|system      = \n|status      = Abandoned\n|locale      = [[Queens, New York City]]\n|start       = [[Willets Point, Queens|Willets Point]] (south)\n|end         = [[Whitestone, Queens|Whitestone]] (north)\n|stations    = 5\n|routes      = \n|daily_ridership = \n|open        = {{Start date|1869}}\n|close       = {{End date|1932|2|19}}\n|owner       = \n|operator    = [[Flushing and North Side Railroad]]<br>[[Long Island Rail Road]]\n|character   = \n|stock       = \n|linelength  = \n|tracklength = \n|tracks = 1\u20132\n|gauge       = {{RailGauge|4ft8.5in}}\n|electrification = 1912<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trainsarefun.com/lirr/branchnotes.htm#Whitestone|title=LIRR Branch Notes|work=trainsarefun.com}}</ref>\n|speed       = \n|elevation   = \n|map         = \n}}\nThe '''Whitestone Branch''' was a branch of the [[Long Island Rail Road]], running north and east along the left bank of the [[Flushing River]] from the [[Port Washington Branch]] near the modern [[Willets Point, Queens|Willets Point]]/[[Flushing, Queens|Flushing]] sections of [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]].  It crossed the river on one of the three bridges that were later torn down for the [[Interstate 678|Van Wyck Expressway]], then ran north along [[Flushing Bay]] and east along the East River to [[Whitestone, Queens|Whitestone]].\n\n==History==\nOriginally conceived as a branch of the [[Flushing and North Side Railroad]] that was intended to lead into [[Westchester County, New York]] (a connection that never materialized) in 1869, it was consolidated into the Long Island Rail Road in 1876 when its owners, the Poppenhusen family, took over the bankrupt LIRR. It later became part of a subsidiary called the [[Long Island City and Flushing Railroad]].\n\nOn October 12, 1912 the branch was electrified.<ref>[http://www.lirrhistory.com/mar2009/WhitestoneLIRR.pdf Electric Trains to Whitestone October 22]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lirrhistory.com/whistone.html|title=Whitestone Branch of LIRR|work=lirrhistory.com}}</ref> In the 1920s the branch began to lose patronage and the LIRR sought to rid itself of the line. There was a proposal for the city-owned [[Independent Subway System]] to buy the line and [[IND Second System|incorporate it]] into the [[New York City Subway]] system. The deal was not successful, most likely due to the numerous [[grade crossing]]s that would have been extremely costly to remove. The [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] allowed the LIRR to abandon the line in 1932.<!--Prior to this, the LIRR built the [[Corona Meadows Team Yard]] along the west side of the tracks north of Whitestone Junction along the Port Washington Branch.<ref>[http://arrts-arrchives.com/cmfrt.html Corona Meadows Yard and Bridge Street Drawbridge (Arrt's Arrchives)]</ref>-->\n\nMost of the branch was removed, except a small section of the line leading to the [[Corona Yard]] which remained well into the 1970s when the LIRR closed the Corona Yard and turned it over to the [[New York City Transit Authority]] for [[New York City Subway|subway]] use. Today only a small section of track remains just east of [[Mets\u2013Willets Point station (LIRR)|Mets\u2013Willets Point station]], branching off from the Port Washington Branch east of the station. The [[Flushing\u2013Main Street station (LIRR)|Flushing\u2013Main Street station]] of the [[Port Washington Branch]] was so named to distinguish it from the Whitestone's Flushing\u2013Bridge Street station. Despite the closing of the Bridge Street station, the LIRR continues to use the name \"Main Street\" for the Port Washington Branch station to this day.\n\nA spur of the line near the Flushing River was abandoned when it went under water in 1983. Private homes have been built over the section of the line in Whitestone Landing.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite book|title=An Assessment of the Transit Service Potential of Inactive Railroad Rights-of-way and Yards Final Report|last=|first=|date=October 1991|publisher=New York City Department of City Planning|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\n==Flushing Bay Freight Spur==\nThe Flushing Bay Freight Spur was a freight-only spur that lead to a freight dock on [[Flushing Bay]] just west of the [[Flushing River]] delta. It began at the Whitestone Branch just north of the junction with the Port Washington Branch, then crossed a junction with a spur of the [[Woodside Branch]] leading to Great Neck Junction and the [[Central Branch (Long Island Rail Road)|Central Branch]], and a second junction with Woodside Branch that lead to the Whitestone Branch,{{refn|1=Seyfried, Vincent F. [[:wikisource:The Long Island Rail Road: A Comprehensive History, Part Two: The Flushing, North Shore & Central Railroad|\"The Long Island Rail Road: A Comprehensive History, Part Two: The Flushing, North Shore & Central Railroad\"]] (1961). \"There were in addition two branches: the four mile spur to Whitestone and a shorter one of one and one quarter miles to Hempstead. The Flushing Creek area was the throat of the system with two main junction points: Whitestone Junction on the west side, where the Whitestone Branch began, and Central Junction on the east bank, where the Central trains turned off for Babylon. When the Woodside Branch opened in April 1874, four more miles of single track were added, plus an additional trestle bridge and connecting spur from Central Junction to the Flushing Bay dock.\"}} and crossing a short bridge before finally terminating at the freight dock. No trace of the spur is known {{as of|2016|lc=yes}}.\n\n==Stations==\nThe entire line was abandoned on February 15, 1932.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Miles from Long Island City\n!Station\n!Date<br>opened\n!Date<br>closed\n!Connections&nbsp;/ notes\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|''[[Port Washington Branch]] diverges''\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|''Junction with [[Flushing Bay Freight Spur]]''\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|''[[Woodside Branch]] diverges''\n|-\n|7.9<ref name=\"flickr.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/20489882171/in/dateposted/|title=$_57-11|work=Flickr - Photo Sharing!}}</ref>\n|[[Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Bridge Street (LIRR station)|Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Bridge Street]]\n|1870\n|1932\n|Named to distinguish it from [[Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Main Street (LIRR station)|Flushing&nbsp;\u2013 Main Street]] station\n|-